 The basic von Thiinen model is (now under different control) in Fig. 1. In 
 a blank plain, surrounding a central market, two 
 crops can be grown-wheat and vegetables. All locations have identical production (features/ qualities/ traits), including profit-making the most of operators, but transport costs 
 to the central market, with (coming from the outside of something)ly serious and stubborn 
 prices, differ by crop. The price of vegetables in the 
 central market (a) is higher than the price of wheat 
 (b) but vegetables are more expensive to transport. 
 Hence, the farm vegetable price falls more quickly 
 than the farm wheat price as distance from the market 
 increases. 3 Beyond point 'c', the farm price of wheat 
 is higher than vegetables. The result is a series of ring-like rings of land use around the central market, pointed to/showed in the bottom part of the graph. In the shaded 
 2 As is so often the case, Paul Samuelson has penetrating ideas about the money-based explanation hidden (under) von Thiinen's work 
 (Samuelson, 1983). 
 3 Note that while output prices fall with distance from the central 
 market, input prices increase. In this simple version of the von 
 Thiinen model, no (bought) inputs are used. 
 
 area, vegetables are grown; in the next ring wheat. Beyond 'd', neither crop is money-making and land is left in 
 its natural state. Even though the productive (features/ qualities/ traits) of the farms are identical, the effect of transport cost is (lowering in number/getting worse) land rents with distance from the 
 central market. 
 Once differences in land working well, prices, transport costs and many markets are introduced, the 
 analysis becomes more complex but the basic ideas 
 of the importance of location and transport cost in deciding/figuring out land use remain. Identifying and explaining those land uses (numbers-based) provides idea-based, 
 data, and modelling challenges. 
 The four summary papers start from the basic ideas of von Thiinen. The first three papers provide 
 reviews of the ideas, book-related, data and examples 
 of analysis in three topic areas-land use in developing countries, the (away from cities)-city-based  (connecting point/way of interacting with something), and quality 
 farming. The final summary paper introduces the 
 econometric issues that come up when location information is available. The first summary paper (Nelson and 
 Geoghegan, 2002) reviews the explanation and practice of 
 modelling land use in developing countries where official data sources almost never include georeferenced values. 
 The use of remotely sensed data provides an especially 
 important other choice. The (giving a reason to do something) issue for the research in this area can be summarised in the phrase "do 
 roads cause (chopping down trees)?" More generally, how does 
 (set of machines) development and policy changes that change  transport costs or prices at the central market change 
 the relative a money-making state of different land use choices? 
 Does it become money-making to convert forested land to 
 some other land use? Papers in this issue by Mertens 
 et al. (2002), Muller and Zeller (2002), Munroe et al. 
 (2002), Swinton (2002), and Vance and Geoghegan 
 (2002) explore land use issues in a few developing 
 countries and with a variety of new and interesting ways of doing things. 
 The second summary paper, by Bell and Irwin 
 (2002), looks at the issues facing planners, real 
 estate developers and nature-lovers at the changing (away from cities)-city-based  (connecting point/way of interacting with something). As suburbs expand and 
 single family home lot sizes grow, pressure follows 
 to convert farming-based land to (where there are lots of homes) real estate 
 or open space such as parks and forest preserves. 
 These issues have received the most attention in developed countries where data sources are (compared to other things) 
 more plentiful and this paper focuses (related to careful studying or deep thinking) 
 ways of doing things in data-rich (surrounding conditions). It should be 
 
 G. C. Nelson/ Farming-based Money flow 27 (2002) 197-200 
 
 noted, however, that the most fast growth of city-based 
 areas is happening in poor countries and 
 the (related to careful studying or deep thinking) ways of doing things presented are related to 
 those (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) also. 
 In all (related to space or existing in space) analysis research, a key issue is the (connected/related) unit of analysis. Should it be US counties, I km 
 square grids from weather satellites, or 30m cells 
 from medium-level (ability to display or measure very small things) satellites or (from high in the air) photos? 
 In a perfect world the scale should be closely connected with the 
 area over which an individual decision-maker has control and information. Little bull et al. (2002) examine 
 quality farming technologies and their (compared to other things) 
 slow acceptance by farmers. This set of technologies 
 (including yield monitors and quality input (online or paper form that asks for a job, money, admission, etc.)) makes it possible to collect data on some 
 important production attributes within a field. They 
 demonstrate that (completing/matching) information can be 
 very important to securing/making sure of the money-making ability of a new technology. The paper by Florax et al. (2002) demonstrates 
 that these ideas are (connected/related) even for Sahelian 
 farmers. 
 The final paper in the summary section (Anselin, 
 2002) introduces the reader to the added/more difficulties in econometric analysis that come up when (related to space or existing in space) 
 relationships exist. In a 'traditional' analysis involving (related to space or existing in space) data (for example, guessing a production 
 function based on input and output data) the location 
 of the (instances of watching, noticing, or making statements) is assumed to be not related. However, if there is some kind of (related to space or existing in space) relationship, either among the (things that change (like test scores) because of other things that you control (like study times)) (a forest at one 
 location causes neighbouring locations to have forests 
 as well) or in the error structure (caused maybe by 
 almost the same  soil types in neighbouring locations), limit/guideline guesses can be inefficient and/or (created unfair thinking in)/(unfair-thinking). Anselin 
 reviews the idea-based issues that come up with (related to space or existing in space) 
 data and analysis, providing ideas from the usual (related to space or existing in space) econometrics books as well as from 
 geostatistics, biostatistics and medical image analysis. Of particular importance to land use analysis is 
 his discussion of hidden/covered up changeable guess with (related to space or existing in space) data. Since land use is the result of an unobservable decision process (choosing a land use that has the 
 highest expected (money made/good thing received)), (not numbers-based) choice guess 
 ways of doing things are used. Anselin reviews the added/more 
 difficulties this causes and suggests ways of doing things to 
 correct for it. 
 The papers in this issue (show or prove) the application 
 of many different kinds of (related to careful studying or deep thinking) ways of doing things (logit, 
 
 199 
 
 probit, danger-related analysis, Bayesian analysis, combining 
 remotely sensed and household survey data, (testing out)), to (related to space or existing in space) money-based problems in many areas of 
 the world (The Amazon, Australia, Bangladesh, Honduras, Kenya, Mexico, Peru, The Sahel, Vietnam). The 
 reader will find interesting new approaches to many 
 important issues talked about in farming-based and (related to a large area) 
 money flow/money-based studies. 
 
